            <p>HENRY ILIOWIZI&#44;<lb/>
                1845 NORHT EIGHTEENTH STREET.<lb/></p>
            <p>PHILADELPHIA&#44; December 17th 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. S. Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>It appears to me our solemn obligation to do everything<lb/> in our power to make the wrongs of our brethren in Russia<lb/> known&#44; and every opportunity should be embraced to reach<lb/> this end.  To do nothing is most assuredly not the wisest<lb/> policy.  If our government is to take any step whatever in<lb/> relation to the Russian Jews&#44; only <sic>influencial</sic> Christians have it<lb/> in their power to bring it about.  Why do nothing&#44; dear doctor&#33;<lb/>  Nothing is sure to come of nothing&#44; while something is<lb/> likely to spring out of something.  Let us show courage as the<lb/> Irish people do in <sic>defence</sic> of our human rights and our manhood.<lb/>  Moreover&#44; having had a meeting with the several clergymen&#44;<lb/> we could not well withdraw&#44; without giving <sic>offence</sic>.  Then<lb/> what harm can it do to meet that &#34;Brotherhood&#44;&#34; anyhow&#63;  I credit<lb/> Sulzberger with a great deal of sound common sense&#59; and do<lb/> not see why we should hesitate in calling black black if any good<lb/> chance is presented.  If we succeed in moving the public we shall have done well.<lb/>  Sincerely yours<lb/> Henry Iliowizi<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
